A user wants to access the website www.foobar.com:

1. The user enters "www.foobar.com" in their browser.
2. The browser sends a DNS request to resolve the domain name.
3. DNS returns the IP address of the load balancer.
4. The browser sends an HTTP/HTTPS request to the load balancer.
5. HAProxy (load balancer) receives the request.
6. HAProxy distributes the request to one of the two backend servers.
7. The selected server’s Nginx (web server) receives the request:
   - If static content is requested, it serves it directly.
   - If dynamic content is needed, it forwards the request to the application server.
8. The application server processes the request:
   - Executes application logic.
   - Queries the MySQL database.
9. The database returns data to the application server.
10. The application server builds the response.
11. Nginx returns the response to HAProxy.
12. HAProxy sends the final response back to the user’s browser.

--------------------------------------------------

Infrastructure components:

- 1 Domain name:
  foobar.com with a "www" A record pointing to the load balancer IP

- 1 Load balancer:
  - HAProxy

- 2 Servers (backend servers), each containing:
  - Web server: Nginx
  - Application server
  - Application files (code base)
  - Database: MySQL

--------------------------------------------------

Why additional elements are added:

Load balancer (HAProxy):
- Distributes incoming traffic across multiple servers
- Improves availability and reliability
- Prevents overload on a single server

Second server:
- Provides redundancy
- Ensures the system continues working if one server fails
- Enables load distribution

--------------------------------------------------

Load balancer distribution algorithm:

Example: Round Robin
- Requests are distributed sequentially across servers
- Server1 → Server2 → Server1 → Server2 ...
- Ensures even distribution under normal conditions

--------------------------------------------------

Active-Active vs Active-Passive:

Active-Active:
- Both servers handle traffic simultaneously
- Improves performance and utilization
- This infrastructure uses Active-Active

Active-Passive:
- One server handles traffic, the other is on standby
- Passive server takes over only if the active one fails

--------------------------------------------------

Database Primary-Replica (Master-Slave) cluster:

- One database acts as Primary (Master):
  - Handles write operations (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE)

- Other database acts as Replica (Slave):
  - Replicates data from the Primary
  - Handles read operations

Replication process:
- Primary logs changes
- Replica reads logs and applies the same changes

--------------------------------------------------

Difference between Primary and Replica (application perspective):

Primary:
- Used for write queries
- Source of truth

Replica:
- Used for read queries
- Reduces load on Primary
- May have slight replication delay

--------------------------------------------------

Issues with this infrastructure:

1. Single Points of Failure (SPOF):
   - Load balancer (only one instance)
   - Database Primary (if it fails, writes stop)

2. Security issues:
   - No firewall to restrict traffic
   - No HTTPS (data transmitted in plain text)

3. No monitoring:
   - No visibility into system health
   - Failures may go undetected
   - No alerting or performance tracking
